blic, each of which has distinct interests, biases, and incentives. Do media representations affect public support for the president and faithfully reflect events in times of diplomatic crisis and war? How do new media--especially Internet news and more partisan outlets--shape public opinion, and how will they alter future conflicts? In answering such questions, Baum and Groeling take an in-depth look at media coverage, elite rhetoric, and public opinion during the Iraq war and other U.S. conflicts abroad. They trace how traditional and new media select stories, how elites frame and sometimes even distort events, and how these dynamics shape public opinion over the course of a conflict. Most of us learn virtually everything we know about foreign policy from media reporting of elite opinions. In War Stories, Baum and Groeling reveal precisely what this means for the future of American foreign policy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aForeign newszUnited States. 0aInternational relationsvPublic opinion. 0aIraq War, 2003-2011vJournalists. 0aIraq War, 2003-2011xJournalists. 0aPress and politicszUnited States. 0aPublic opinionzUnited States. 0aSOCIAL SCIENCEvMedia Studies. 0aWarvPress coveragezUnited States. 0aWarvPress coverage. 0aWarxPress coveragezUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / General.2bisacsh1 aGroeling, Tim J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140083218740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400832187423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400832187.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEB